510eff4f-2b1f-5b23-a329-8c19f43773ed.title: Annual leave
510eff4f-2b1f-5b23-a329-8c19f43773ed.metaDescription: Find out how much holiday you have each year, how to book time off and buy more holiday, what to do if you’re ill when on leave, and other details of how holiday works
510eff4f-2b1f-5b23-a329-8c19f43773ed.intro: You get at least 25 days’ holiday to use between 1 April and 31 March, and after working five years you get an extra five days’ holiday.
content:
If you want to book holiday go to Employee Self Service (ESS) on SAP. If you don’t yet have access to SAP, book holiday with your line manager and then enter it into SAP when you have access. The amount of holiday you get will depend on your terms and conditions. The holiday entitlements below are for employees on Buckinghamshire Council Terms and Conditions. If you are on AVDC, BCC, C&SB, or WDC terms and conditions, you will get a different amount of holiday. For more information please use the links below: - [Aylesbury Vale District Council](https://avdc.app.box.com/folder/49049170045 "Aylesbury Vale District Council Information") - [Buckinghamshire County Council](https://intranet.buckscc.gov.uk/how-do-i/human-resources/what-you-can-expect-from-us/leave/annual-leave/ "Buckinghamshire County Council Information") - [Chiltern and South Bucks Council](https://crmstaff.chilternandsouthbucks.gov.uk/annual-leave "Chiltern and South Bucks Information ") - [Wycombe District Council](https://wycopedia.wycombe.gov.uk/pages/My-employment/Employment-policies/Local-terms-and-conditions-of-employment.aspx "Wycombe District Council Information")

When you start working for the council, or when you leave, the amount of holiday you’re entitled to is worked out according to the number of days you’ll have worked during the current leave year, ie: Your total annual leave entitlement ÷ 365 x the number of days worked. ### Part-time entitlement If you’re a part-time employee your annual leave is worked out on a pro-rata basis, and calculated in hours. Your quota is shown in SAP Employee Self Service (ESS). > Public holidays will be automatically credited to you, but at the beginning of the leave year you need to book all public holidays as a full working day. If you begin working part way through the leave year, SAP Portal will automatically calculate the hours. ### Term time only entitlement If you work on a term-time only basis, you don’t get any holiday in addition to the time you’re off when not working. You may be able to ‘buy’ up to two weeks’ extra holiday. You pay for the extra time by having the appropriate amount deducted from your salary. You won’t be able to do this if: - You’re on a contract of less than 12 months. - You work in a school or work only term time. - Buying more holiday would take your hourly rate below the National Minimum Wage or National Living Wage. After you’ve worked for the council for five years you’ll receive an extra five days’ leave. If you work part time, the extra holiday will be pro rata. If you’re full time you get public holidays off and you don’t need to enter this in SAP Employee Self Service (ESS). If you're part-time you get a pro rata number of hours off for each public holiday. This is automatically added on to your annual leave amount. For example if you work 30 hours per week then you’re entitled to six hours for each bank holiday, and this will be added to your annual leave at the beginning of the new leave year. If a public holiday falls on one of your working days, you’ll need to book it off as a full working day. If a bank holiday falls on a non-working day, SAP will not deduct the hours and you will gain a one-fifth allowance. If you get ill when on holiday (or over a bank holiday) we’ll count this as having time off sick, but you will need a doctor’s certificate from a GP or hospital. Tell your manager as soon as you can, and they will enter this absence on SAP via Manager Self Service (MSS). We encourage you to take any remaining holiday before you go off on maternity, paternity or adoption leave. If you do have any left over it may be added to the end of your time away. For details see the [Family Friendly Leave Guidance](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/3KS9J2G1w1r2Hn7nxbph70/ee7e776e5babc300c36feccf5cdf530b/BC_Family_Friendly_Guidance_Mar_2020.doc). The time you’re away on maternity, paternity or adoption leave will count towards the five years’ service total. Generally you should use up your holiday quota before you stop working here. In some circumstances you may get a payment for any unused holiday included in your final salary payment. However, sometimes you may have taken more holiday than you’re entitled to at the point when you leave (if it’s part way through the leave year). If so, the appropriate amount will be deducted from your final salary payment

d95dbc68-e229-5dd8-8a67-de32e90c3a11.intro:
We are proud to partner the national Step Up to Social Work programme, which provides a great opportunity to retrain to be a social worker and be able to continue to fund your living costs while you are studying.

Social work is both a challenging and rewarding career through which you can make a real difference for vulnerable children and families.

If you want to make the career move, and you meet the eligibility criteria below, we encourage you to apply. Online applications are open until 7 April via the [Step Up to Social Work application website](https://www5.i-grasp.com/fe/tpl_capita78.asp?newms=info1 "Step Up to Social Work application website")

Please note, this is an intensive 14-month full time diploma, therefore you would need to resign from your current job if you are successful in getting a place on the programme.

- £19,833 tax free bursary payment over the duration of the programme
- Zero tuition fees
- Fast track – 14 months to become a social worker
- Practice-led training programme
- Training is delivered by the University of Bedfordshire
- Opportunity to complete the Masters component within 2 years of qualifying (self-funded)
- we will be hosting 6 students 
- critical reflection group and learner guide
- hands-on 70-day adult and 100 children's service placements with practice educators/on-site supervision

- This is a postgraduate programme so you will need a minimum 2:1 level 6 degree qualification (in any discipline other than in Social Work) or
- A minimum 2:2 honours degree plus a higher degree (level 7 or above, which can include a Master's degree or a Postgraduate Certificate of Education, in any discipline other than Social Work)
- Grade C or above GSCE in English/ English Language and Maths (or recognised equivalent)
- Experience of working with children, young people and families, and who can demonstrate their maturity and emotional resilience
- The right to remain and work in England

930fdc5f-ac67-506f-b847-6229569bf26a.title: Your performance review
930fdc5f-ac67-506f-b847-6229569bf26a.metaDescription: Find out how our performance reviews work, what your manager looks at when they rate your performance and what to do if you disagree with your performance rating.
930fdc5f-ac67-506f-b847-6229569bf26a.intro:
Twice a year you and your manager will meet formally to review how you’re performing. Your manager will then rate your performance, based on whether you’re meeting the goals you’ve agreed and the requirements of your role, as well as your overall behaviour.

We have produced two short videos to help managers with appraising performance and how to record it on SAP.

__Appraising performance__
<iframe style="width:100%; height:30vw;" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/WVSWG-a0_zo" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

__Recording performance reviews onto SAP__
<iframe style="width:100%; height:30vw;" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/Z-cK0deetsw" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
content:
Your performance review is a formal assessment of how well you’re doing your job. Your manager will look at your performance and give you a rating. A record of your conversation will be logged on our admin system, SAP.
Everyone has a formal performance review twice a year. You’ll have a half-year review in September, which should give you an idea of how you’re performing. You’ll have a full year review in March, which gives you your performance rating for the year. It’s checked and signed off in April.
When your manager decides what rating to give you they will consider whether or not you have:

- Met the goals you’ve agreed together every quarter. 
- Demonstrated our values and behaviours in the way you do your work. 
- Done what you’re expected to do in your job, including whether you’ve completed the essential training and fulfilled any other requirements for your role.
Our values ‘PACT’ – Proud, Ambitious, Collaborative and Trustworthy – describe how we work. Your manager will think about how well you’re meeting each of these. 

## Proud
Do you set high standards, perform at your best and care about the customer?

## Ambitious
Do you want to learn new things, try out new ideas and make a positive difference in the job?

## Collaborative
Do you lend a hand, share ideas, learn from others and look at things from other people’s perspectives?

## Trustworthy
Do you do what you say you’ll do, show initiative, speak up when things aren’t right and behave professionally?
Having reviewed your performance, your manager can give you five possible ratings. 

Most people should get an ‘Achieves’ – this means you’re doing your job well, and you deserve thanks and recognition for this. However, in exceptional circumstances some people will get one of the other four ratings. 

### Outstanding 
This means you have consistently exceeded standards and expectations – perhaps because of exceptional circumstances. You’re seen as someone who stands out in the way you get things done and as an exceptional role model.

### Exceeds
You have often exceeded standards and expectations, possibly because there have been unusual challenges. Your colleagues recognise you as someone who goes the extra mile.

### Achieves
You meet the standards and expectations that come with your job. You achieve the goals you’re set, and you work in a way that demonstrates our values. We think you’re a good employee – and that’s something to be proud of.

### Needs development
You are new or have been here less than six months. Or you’re falling short of our standards and expectations. You’re not doing your work in a way that meets our values.

### Unsatisfactory
You’re failing to meet our standards and expectations. The way you do your work isn’t in line with our values.

### What to do if you disagree with your end of year performance rating
You can appeal against your end of year performance rating if you disagree with it. The first step is to make an informal appeal to your grandparent manager (your manager’s manager) when it’s awarded. If you want to take things further, you can make a formal appeal to an independent service director before your rating’s signed off in April.

### How does my performance rating affect my pay?

This will depend on your terms and conditions. Please see [this document](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/3WeNFczYTxeQVO1ksANXp9/6c51bf6695b20bde47e115ff4f475d61/How_C4P_ratings_affect_pay.rtf) for details of how your performance rating will affect your pay.
You may appeal your Provisional or Final End of Year rating if you don't agree with the rating, however you cannot appeal your Indicative Mid-year rating. Please note you cannot appeal against an End of Year rating if a Needs Development rating that has been triggered as a result of failing to comply with mandatory elearning. The below appeal process applies to all employees below Service Director level. 

### Informal Appeal
The first stage of any appeal is to raise your concerns informally with your grandparent (next but one) manager when you are notified of your assessment, so that this can be reviewed as part of the grandparent quality check. The grandparent manager will meet with you to review your case and give their decision. It is the expectation that the vast majority of appeals against ratings should be settled this way. As an exception, if the matter is not resolved at this point an employee may make a formal appeal.

### Formal Appeal
- Employees must use the [Notification of Appeal Form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/44216fFbpfZHz6xdHwwXZO/d345293f232615f6bc55975f552ad195/Notification_of_Appeal_Form.docx) to make their appeal.
- Appeal forms must be sent to the HR Service Desk no later than 30 April. 
- HR Service Desk will acknowledge receipt and put the appeals process in motion.

### Appeal Hearing
- Appeals will be heard by the Hearing Officer who will be a Service Director who is independent from the employee’s service area. 
- The employee may be accompanied at the appeal by a work colleague or accredited union representative. They may not be accompanied by family members, friends who are not work colleagues or legal representatives.
- If the employee is not available to attend the scheduled appeal meeting it may be necessary to hear the appeal without the employee being present.
- The appeal outcome will be given in writing to the employee, within 5 working days of the appeal hearing.  There is no further right of appeal against the Service Director’s decision. 
- If the appeal results in a change of assessment that impacts on Contribution based pay, an adjustment will be made to salary in the next payroll period.

bead0121-d209-5eaa-907c-d64ca7a314a5.title: Upskilling apprenticeships
bead0121-d209-5eaa-907c-d64ca7a314a5.intro: You can develop your professional or management skills by undertaking an apprenticeship relevant to your role. These are nationally recognised work-based programmes and lead to accredited professional qualifications.  They’re ideal if you’re wanting to increase your skills as part of your career development.
content:
- Workshops - monthly interactive workshops with a group of peers. All workshops are led by qualified tutors with a wealth of experience.  
- Resources - students have access to high quality online resources and reference materials and will create a learning log.
- Personal tutor – a dedicated tutor from the apprenticeship training provider who will be there to support you. Bringing their expertise they will guide throughout the programme. 
- Line manager - support is vital to success, working together to develop skills will benefit the whole team.
- Peer support - creates a supportive environment to learn. Studying in groups builds strong bonds and builds networks. 
- Assessment – there are milestones throughout the programme with an end point assessment to establish grades achieved.
- Off-the-job learning – 20% of working time must be dedicated to learning. This can be made up of training sessions, shadowing, mentor assessments, gaining practical application of the learning, work experience placements, assignments, and possibly secondments for higher level apprenticeships

1.	First step is to talk to your line manager and discuss how an apprenticeship could help you develop your career. Your line manager will need to agree the request with your Service Director.

2.	Search the available apprenticeship programmes to see what is suitable to your role and career aspirations on the [Bucks Adult Learning](https://www.adultlearningbc.ac.uk/apprenticeships/ "Bucks Adult Learning ")  and the [Institute of Apprenticeships](https://www.instituteforapprenticeships.org/ "Institute of Apprenticeships") websites. Contact the apprenticeships co-ordinator if you cannot find what you’re looking for.

3.	When you have found the apprenticeship programme that is right for you, and it has been agreed with your manager and Service Director, complete the [Upskilling Apprenticeship Nomination Form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/1udCHuUxriVYju6CleBBOZ/c169af526a2af02c3e9ad104af7c253c/Nomination_Form-Staff_Upskilling_Apprent.docx) and email to apprenticeships@buckinghamshire.gov.uk.

- Upskilling apprenticeships are open to all job grades, but you will need the scope within your role to cover the skills and knowledge requirements of your chosen apprenticeship and be able to evidence that you will gain ‘significant new skills’ by undertaking the apprenticeship
- An apprenticeship programme is a big commitment and will require you to be able to work on your own between tutor and training sessions as well as balance your work demands alongside studying
- You must spend at least 20% of your contracted hours in off-the-job-learning, and you and your manager will need to evidence this throughout the programme.
- You and your line manager will sign an Employer Apprenticeship Agreement which sets out the expectations of you as you undertake the apprenticeship, and their commitment to support you
- Apprenticeships take between 18 months and 4 years depending on the level and discipline
- Your salary stays the same whilst you undertake an apprenticeship and there are no changes to your terms and conditions of employment. Training costs are paid for by Apprenticeship Levy Funds.
- You will need to be on a permanent contract to be eligible

- Make time to regularly join in with the tutor-apprentice meetings. Even if it’s just for the first 10 minutes of the session, it’s your chance to keep up to date with their progress and show your support. It will also help you plan any new areas of work you could be giving them and support your C4P discussions. At the very least, you MUST attend any quarterly 3-way reviews between the training provider, you and your team member.
- Help your staff member to manage their time effectively and, if needs be, delegate tasks to other team members to allow them to take the 20% off-the-job-learning time.
- Support your member of staff to fulfil the 20% off-the-job-learning requirement. Remember that this is to spend 20% of their working hours (over the duration of the programme) learning new skills/completing assignments/work shadowing/attending actual training sessions. The tutor can help you determine what counts towards the 20%.
- Flag up any concerns you have about progress with the tutor. They are there to advise you as an employer and will want to work with you so that your staff member successfully completes their qualification.
- Feedback to apprenticeships@buckinghamshire.gov.uk if you have any concerns about the training provider’s delivery of the apprenticeship, which you cannot resolve with them yourself.

Whether you’re new to a management role (people or project) or looking to take the next step to a more senior, strategic position, we have an apprenticeship programme that could help you develop the skills, confidence and experience to help you thrive. 

[Find out more Management apprenticeships](https://youandwork.buckscc.gov.uk/training-and-development/on-demand-management-apprenticeship-programmes "https://youandwork.buckscc.gov.uk/training-and-development/on-demand-management-apprenticeship-programmes")

458dc126-bc87-5700-af41-d7b61aff4a95.title: New Talent apprenticeships
458dc126-bc87-5700-af41-d7b61aff4a95.intro: New Talent apprenticeships are entry level apprenticeships for those just starting out in their chosen career. Programmes are available in a diverse range of professions and skill areas here at the council, from energy technician to business administration apprenticeships.
content:
### Leon, Apprentice Technical Officer
[Meet Leon](//videos.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/7ls1OJ6sF1xOaD2CMAWiCv/0a698d8f1f8314ed28eca994e8017ce0/Leon_NAW_2021_Q___A.mp4), an Apprentice Technical Officer here at Buckinghamshire Council. We asked him some FAQs about his experience of doing an Apprenticeship with us.

### Lauren, Business Support Coordinator

![Lauren Job Profile Wide 1](//images.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/6kbDYRdtnahMkY8joX7UK8/54f215aa3fa25257b1102e5317f47b23/Lauren_Job_Profile_Wide_1.jpg)

![Lauren Job Profile Wide 2](//images.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/3Jq7ZOHMFTooJ8MeVyERoM/ee148c998575581c64c3fb391521e25b/Lauren_Job_Profile_Wide_2.jpg)

### Alicia, Business Development Trainee
![Alicia Blog Standard 1](//images.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/1Tmuw8442EjTbIji2yTS5j/55b62f43ff1ddd44e0af15dba77d6659/Alicia_Blog_Standard_1.jpg)

![Alicia Blog Standard 2](//images.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/70WRDidQQSDzqkobAyOxKX/8dd5543516d8e9d7ad9ec475778d8120/Alicia_Blog_Standard_2.png)

If you have an apprenticeship opportunity in your team, please get in touch with our dedicated apprenticeship co-ordinator by emailing apprenticeships@buckinghamshire.gov.uk. 

We are on hand to support you throughout, from recruitment and selection right through to completion of the programme. You’ll also be invited to join our quarterly ‘Apprentice Line Managers Forum’ to network with other apprentice managers and share good practice, swap ideas and discuss relevant issues. 

This [handy flowchart](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/4dDJFefUnJ1kAa5NmwY43r/0f9d6cd5e3686725aaec46d1c9be8771/Acrobat_Document.pdf) sets out the steps of the recruitment journey. 

### Key contractual need to knows… 
‘New Talent’ apprentices:
- are employed on a fixed-term contract for the duration of their apprenticeship
- are not part of Contribution Based Pay, but should have regular, documented supervision sessions with clear objectives, that feed into a light-touch C4P process
- are subject to the usual 6 months probationary period
- are entitled to 25 days annual leave p.a. plus bank holidays
- join the LGPS pension scheme but can opt out
- must spend 20% of their time learning new skills
- only the training costs are covered by Apprenticeship Levy Funds

Regular supervision sessions are crucial, and we recommend that you also allocate a “buddy” to provide additional support for your apprentice. A buddy can answer questions and support them in a more informal way. The buddy should be a colleague in the same team, perhaps someone who has recently completed an apprenticeship themselves, and who has a positive attitude, patience and good communication skills.

Your apprentice will be assigned a personal tutor from the training provider who they will meet with every 3-6 weeks to check in and carry out observations, discussions, training/mentoring etc. The tutor will also carry out 10-12 week progress reviews which will involve you as well as the apprentice to discuss progress made in their learning programme both at work and training sessions.
Apprentices must spend at least 20% off-the-job recorded training or learning, equivalent to one day a week for a full-time apprentice. This can be split up, for example, two afternoons a week but must take place within the apprentice’s paid working hours. 

‘Off-the-job training’ is any “learning which is undertaken outside of the normal day-to-day working environment and leads towards the achievement of an apprenticeship.” The following do not count as ‘off-the-job training’ and are outside the 20%:

- English and Math tutoring (up to level two) 
- Progress reviews or on-programme assessment required for an apprenticeship
- Training which takes place outside the apprentice’s paid working hours
- Carrying out tasks in which the learner is competent as part of normal work activities

If you have any performance management issues at any stage with your apprentice, please contact the apprenticeship co-ordinator in the first instance. We will work with you and the apprentice to try to resolve the issues informally. If necessary, action can be escalated to formal procedures, and you can receive advice and support should it reach this stage. 

Your apprentice will especially need targeted support in the first few months, so please factor in this time investment. If it still doesn’t work out during the probationary period, you will need to make sure that you have evidence that you have provided all possible support and all possible training.

It’s important that we retain the new talent we have invested in. With that in mind, you should be thinking ahead to what the next steps for your apprentice could be once they have completed. A career-graded post attached to the next level of apprenticeship for example could be an option.

If there are no suitable job opportunities available at the council, an end-of-Contract Consultation will need to be carried out with the apprentice.

You may need to extend the contract slightly to enable your apprentice to complete their qualification. Or if the apprentice completes earlier than the expected end date, the contract can also be shortened. content:
The Level 3 Team Leader apprenticeship programme is perfect for team leaders or supervisors in a first line management role, with operational and project responsibilities or responsibility for managing a team. The Level 3 programme takes between 12-18 months to complete. 

You’ll learn about:
- Managing people
- Managing change and dealing with conflict
- Communication 
- Problem solving and decision making
- Building relationships and collaboration

You’ll learn about:

- Leading change and innovation
- Communication, in person and remotely
- Problem solving and decision making
- Building relationships and collaboration
- Project management
- Self-awareness and time management

content:
Our LEADER Framework for Buckinghamshire Council is an acronym which sets out the skills and behaviours of what it takes to be a great Buckinghamshire manager. The LEADER Framework underpins the entire programme so we want all managers to become really familiar with it and know the standard we are aspiring to. Watch our 'Introducing the LEADER Framework' video which takes you through what the LEADER acronym stands for:


## LEADER behaviours ![Leader framework](//images.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/4f7XztOG6JAwrih3Y9MSrt/6e7365d19d4702356524c642e2203005/Leader_framework.PNG)

The Manager Essentials is where it all starts and your foundation as a Buckinghamshire manager. They are the core requirements we expect of each of our managers, independent of service area or level.

The Manager Essentials are split into three parts: developing yourself as a manager, people management skills, and other ‘need to knows’, which cover resources and corporate responsibilities, such as finance and health and safety.

The Manager Essentials Workbook below will introduce you to all the essentials and help you identify if there are any areas that need strengthening. If you do have gaps in knowledge or a skill you want to practise or improve, then we have a growing library of learning resources at hand.

These resources can be accessed through the Manager Essentials page on the [Learning Hub](https://buckinghamshirecouncil.learningpool.com/login/index.php "Learning Hub").

7b0e05d9-a0bb-55c8-a0fc-b1b64b9ab04b.intro: The more you and your manager communicate, the easier it is for your manager to support you. It’s a good idea to have frequent chats about your short term goals, and then review these every three months. You’ll also have a more formal review twice a year to check on how you’re doing.
content:
Talking regularly with your manager is a good way of keeping in touch about the work you’re doing. It’s also a chance to talk through what’s going well and not so well and get support. 

If you have a query or a problem, ask your manager for a chat there and then (face to face or by phone, etc). It’s much better to talk about it immediately than wait for a scheduled meeting.
Every three months, it’s a good idea for you and your manager to have a more formal meeting. This will help you set your direction and review how you’re performing. 
You must have two formal performance reviews each year in March and September. Your manager then rates how you’ve performed, based on how well you’ve met your goals, how well your behaviour matches our values ‘PACT’, and how well you’ve carried out your role.
There are six key online training modules that all of us need to go on. Think of them as the basic ground rules of how we work safely together.

6b752f57-013b-555e-8ba8-c6228551064c.title: Values at work
6b752f57-013b-555e-8ba8-c6228551064c.metaDescription: Find out about our PACT values and why they're important to us.
6b752f57-013b-555e-8ba8-c6228551064c.intro:
Proud. Ambitious. Collaborative. Trustworthy. Our PACT values are central to our workplace culture. They are what we stand for as an organisation. You’ll see them in how we work with each other, and how we serve Buckinghamshire’s residents. Find out on this page how you can live them too.

Colleagues have been sharing what the values mean to them, and how they've seen them in action in this short video:

<iframe style="width:100%; height:40vw;" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/4k0s7yErglk" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe>
content:
You are motivated to make a positive difference for our people and communities and are proud to be part of Buckinghamshire Council.

__Be proud at work by:__
- Showing you care for work and setting high standards.
- Performing to your best every day.
- Caring about customers and their needs. 
- Upholding the reputation of the council and your service.
- Being proud of the role you play to deliver better outcomes for people in Buckinghamshire. 
You are excited about our organisation and have confidence in our ability to meet the challenges ahead. 

__Be ambitious at work by:__
- Being ambitious to learn, develop and fulfil potential  at work.
- Being keen to try out new ideas to make a positive difference for service users.
- Looking for solutions rather than dwelling on problems. 
- Being creative and curious about doing things better. 
You work well with others and across our partner organisations, making connections and understanding the bigger picture.

__Be collaborative at work by:__
- Happily lending a hand and getting involved if you can help. 
- Sharing ideas; asking questions and showing interest in the work other people do. 
- Making an effort to understand the bigger picture - to see how systems and processes join up. 
- Looking at things from different perspectives 
You take responsibility for your work and are trusted to perform your job to the best of your ability. 

__Be trustworthy at work by:__
- Being accountable for your actions.
- Being quick to respond and show initiative. 
- Being willing to speak up when things aren't right. 
- Behaving professionally and to professional standards.  
- Following our code of conduct and taking corporate standards seriously.

cb63c7f4-b274-5c7c-b678-3d353b047388.title: Time off sick
cb63c7f4-b274-5c7c-b678-3d353b047388.metaDescription: This section explains what happens with work and illness – what to do if you’re ill or have a doctor’s appointment, what happens with your pay when you’re off sick, long term illness and frequent illness.
cb63c7f4-b274-5c7c-b678-3d353b047388.intro:
- On the first day you’re ill, phone your manager as soon as possible.
- When you get back to work, fill in a form with details of your illness: [Self certification form (Word doc, 21k)](https://assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/3h1U9c0QLTg8UCnFd1Uoc/c2cddb2bb1dcbad18ed0cea8fea2196d/self-certification-form.docx)
- If you’re off work for more than seven days you’ll need a medical certificate.
content:
Stay in touch with your manager, so they know how you’re doing and if your illness is lasting longer than expected. Your manager will record your absence on our admin
system, SAP.

When you get back to work, catch up with your manager. They will tell you anything
you’ve missed, and you can explain about your illness and any underlying factors. They will then fill in a return to work discussion form. 

- [Return to Work Form: Up to 7 Days Off](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/1umU4bfX0NursCM5hdGlrh/74be1e9a76785ec41808fb81e004d8da/Return_to_Work_Short_Term_Absence.rtf "Return to Work Form for up to 7 Days Off")
- [Return to Work Form: More than 7 Days Off](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/2KFgm51C7UYvGCmxhAW2d8/1b7faf9aa074c5ed22f0e55e5ec0a69b/Return_to_Work_Longer_Term_Absence.rtf "Return to Work Form for more than 7 Days Off")

Try and arrange doctor and dentist appointments outside work hours, but if not
then try to be off work for no more than an hour. If you need to take longer, talk to your manager first and they may agree extra time if you need it.
To start with you’ll be paid as normal when you’re off ill. How long you’ll continue to be paid depends on how long you’ve worked at the council.
If you’re ill for longer than 28 days, it’s considered long term illness. We’ll need to find out more about your illness and then see how we can help you back to work.

Everyone gets ill from time to time, but if it happens too often it can become a problem.

All days off sick are recorded so we can pick up on this.
You’ll need to meet your manager to discuss your illness if:

- You’re off ill more than three times in a 6-month period
- Your time off ill has a noticeable pattern, for example if it always happens around weekends or special occasions.

Full details on time off sick are in our [Health and Attendance Policy](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/6Ramm6Mt2ISpE8pahajgAB/ff98bf0eaecbef2895de7941a92e54ac/BC_Health_and_Attendance_Policy_v1.4_Mar_2020.doc "Health and Attendance Policy"). c46f43ce-d8cb-585c-861a-8def520a0959.title: How to behave at work
c46f43ce-d8cb-585c-861a-8def520a0959.metaDescription: Find out how we are expected to conduct ourselves while working for the council, based on our code of conduct.
c46f43ce-d8cb-585c-861a-8def520a0959.intro:
How we behave and conduct ourselves at work is important. Our Code of Conduct is based on the idea that everyone who works here treats each other with dignity and respect. 

All of us, managers and employees, have a duty to behave well at work. Your manager should make sure you know how you’re expected to behave to work. 

The principles of how we behave are written down in detail in our [Code of Conduct](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/gN5IUSKGMQu2kP09foE8M/daf18a09bcfc8578851e299c884d5cd8/BC_Code_of_Conduct_Services_Mar_2020__1_.rtf), but this page gives an overview of how we’re expected to behave.
content:
Anyone who works with children, young people or adults with care and support needs has a duty to keep them safe. 

Please read our [Code of Conduct and Appendices](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/3ANfbzjWTXEvIkpNh4PMbl/e375157eb0bdba249811c70a1ac66683/BC_Code_of_Conduct_Services_Mar_2020.docx "Code of Conduct") to find out more.
All personal data and information should be respected and kept safe. This includes any personal information about councillors. You should never:

- Use information for your own personal gain or pass it on to other people
- Record a meeting without consent
- Post sensitive information about a colleague or the council on social media without them knowing

We all sign a confidentiality agreement when we join the council to say you will follow our policy on personal data.
All council business should be carried out to high standards. You must follow the law in anything commercial or business related and never take part in fraud or corruption.

Read our [Anti-fraud and Corruption Policy](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/1G8aA86Li73BbNwCmorurO/b40cfbce73dd92a5e6d64d2293db7976/Anti-fraud_and_Corruption_Policy_v1.2.rtf "Anti Fraud and Corruption Policy").
We won’t interfere in your private life unless it is having an effect on council services or could damage the reputation of the council. 

But you must never have a close personal relationship with a child or young person under the age of 18, or 19 if still at school, or with an adult with care and support needs who you meet through work.
If you know someone who is applying for a post at the council, then you must not be involved in their recruitment process.

Some council posts are politically restricted. This means the person in post can’t apply to become a member of a local authority or the House of Commons. Your director or a senior manager can tell you more about this.
You must always tell your manager if you’re working for another organisation, or thinking about working for someone else at the same time as working for the council.
All ICT equipment belongs to the council and should always be used in the right way. You can get into trouble if you access any content that’s inappropriate or illegal or misuse equipment. 

Please take care using any technology at work such as mobile phones, text messages, emails, digital cameras, videos, web cams, websites and blogs.

Always follow the council’s guidance on use of ICT and social media. Please read the Code of Conduct and [ICT Policies](https://buckinghamshire.itpolicysystem.com/acceptableuse.html "ICT Policies") to find out more.
We want the council to be a safe and healthy environment. Don’t bring drugs or alcohol into work, use them at work or be under the influence while at work. 

Read our [Code of Conduct](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/3ANfbzjWTXEvIkpNh4PMbl/e375157eb0bdba249811c70a1ac66683/BC_Code_of_Conduct_Services_Mar_2020.docx) to find out more.

0de22c92-8efc-5818-a53f-5683badc699d.title: New starters and P45
0de22c92-8efc-5818-a53f-5683badc699d.metaDescription: What to do with your P45 when you start working at the council, and what to do if you don’t have a P45
0de22c92-8efc-5818-a53f-5683badc699d.intro:
Everyone should get a P45 from their last employer when they stop working for them. Your P45 is a record of all your pay and tax taken so far in the current
year.
content:
If you don’t have a P45, you will need to fill out a [starter checklist](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/paye-starter-checklist "Starter Checklist"). This might be because:

- You’re starting your first job
- You’re working here as a second job at the same time as another one
- You don’t have a P45 for the current tax year

###  Zero T (0T) tax codes
If you don’t have a P45 or you haven’t filled in a new starter checklist before your first payday, you may be put on a Zero T (0T) tax code. The trouble is that this will probably mean you pay more tax than you should. However, if you do pay too much tax, you may be entitled to get the money back but it may take some time and you may have to [contact HMRC directly](https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/hm-revenue-customs/contact/income-tax-enquiries-for-individuals-pensioners-and-employees "Contact HMRC").

You can find out if you’re on a 0T tax code by looking at your payslip.

### Changing your tax code
If you find you’re on a 0T tax code, make sure you submit your P45 or new starter checklist and quote your individual payroll number which you should find on your last payslip. If you send the documents to HR in time we may be able to amend your tax code before your next payslip goes out. Also, if HM Revenue & Customs (HMRC) send you a tax code directly through the post, we won't be able to apply it, we'll need HMRC to contact us directly to tell us what the code is.

### The wrong tax code
If HMRC issue an electronic tax code directly to you then there isn’t anything we can do to change it. They will only deal with you directly, so you’ll need to  phone them on [0300 200 3300](tel:03002003300). Once we receive a new tax code directly from HMRC, we will apply it as soon as we can. Depending on when we receive it, it may not be until the following month's pay that you see the change.

adbb710d-ad56-5d45-8fc2-57418189b5c3.title: Employee transfers
adbb710d-ad56-5d45-8fc2-57418189b5c3.metaDescription: How employees find another role at the council if they can’t continue their current role. This includes people who have been made redundant, are too ill to continue with their current role or coming to the end of a fixed term contract
adbb710d-ad56-5d45-8fc2-57418189b5c3.intro: If you can’t continue with your current role at the council, joining the Employee Transfer Register will make it easier to find a new role. You’ll be able to see all the new roles and get a guaranteed interview if you meet the essential criteria for the role.
content:
You can join the Employee Transfer Register if you’re:

- Being made redundant 
- Coming to the end of a fixed term contract
- Finding it hard to continue with your current role because of disability
- Suffering from illness and may have to leave your current role

Sometimes people in other situations can join too. 

To join the register, fill in the [Employee transfer register referral form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/1mEWVNrczB3ECzKicT5KGS/28907be0dcec6071f1bc090db8133aac/Employee-Transfer-Register-Referral-Form-August-2019.docx "Employee Transfer Register Referral Form") and send it to HR at [hrservicedesk@buckinghamshire.gov.uk](mailto:hrservicedesk@buckinghamshire.gov.uk)
People on the register who are being made redundant are normally considered first for a new role. Anyone who is facing redundancy and also on maternity, adoption, or shared parental leave takes priority over others facing redundancy. 
For a new role to count as suitable alternative employment it needs to have broadly the same kind of pay, responsibilities, working conditions, etc, as your current job. If you say no to suitable alternative employment you won’t be entitled to a redundancy payment. 
It’s up to you to check the register for jobs that might suit you. Apply by filling in an application form as normal, and if you meet the essential criteria for the role, you’ll be asked for an interview. After all the interviews have taken place, the best candidate for the job will be offered the job, whether or not they’re on the register. 
If you’re made redundant and find a new role which is significantly different from your old one, you’ll have an initial four week trial period. This gives both you and your manager a chance to see if the role suits you.

7d31c1d3-4eff-576d-bc56-67655c0d2072.title: Long term illness
7d31c1d3-4eff-576d-bc56-67655c0d2072.metaDescription: Find out what happens if you’re off work because of illness for more than 28 days, and how the council will help you get to work.
7d31c1d3-4eff-576d-bc56-67655c0d2072.intro:
If you’ve been away from work for 28 days or more, we’ll need to meet you to
find out more about your illness. We won’t put pressure on you to come
back, but we will do all we can to help you get ready for work again.
content:
Your manager will get in touch with you to find out more about your situation and set up a meeting. It’s important you attend the meetings your manager arranges.

If you don’t feel well enough to meet at work, then you can ask to meet somewhere else, for example at home.

During the meeting, your manager will find out more about your illness. Afterwards they may ask you to see an occupational health adviser who specialises in the well-being of people at work. The health adviser will get a clear understanding of the health problems you’re facing and how they may affect your ability to work. They may ask to see a medical report from your GP.

Your manager will then make a plan to help you get back to work. For example, you might start back at work for only a few hours per week and then gradually build up to your full time hours. Or you may need support when you come back to work, such as special equipment like a supportive chair or longer comfort breaks.

Your manager will arrange a follow up meetingto see if you're improving and decide what to do next.

If you’re still not able to work after the plan has been put into action, you’ll need to go to a formal meeting. You can take a work colleague with you or someone from your Union, if you want to. If you haven't already spoken with occupational health, your manager might ask you to talk to a health adviser. Your manager will look at all the information and decide what to do next.

This could include reducing your work hours, bringing in special equipment to help you at work, as well as any other adjustments we can make to help you get back on track.

If your illness means you still can’t work, we’ll have to consider all other options. 

These include making adjustments to how you work, or suggesting other roles for you, and if you need to stop working for the council completely. We will discuss all this with you in detail before making any decision, and make sure we have the most up to date information from your doctor. 

We’ll follow our Health and Attendance policy and the Equality Act 2010 at every stage. 

If you do need to stop working for the council, you may be able to take early retirement for health reasons if you have more than 3 months’ pensionable service. 

But before we get to that point, we will still do all we can to get you back to work with us.
If you don’t agree with what’s decided at stage 3, you can appeal against it. Your appeal will be seen by someone other than your manager, so you get treated fairly.
You will continue to be paid your normal salary for a period of time, before moving to half pay. How long this lasts depends on how long you’ve worked at the council.

2b22ee8a-47ca-5bfd-9870-fd1bcca64d37.title: How we recruit people
2b22ee8a-47ca-5bfd-9870-fd1bcca64d37.metaDescription: Find out how to decide whether to recruit someone, how to advertise your job vacancy, what to think about before you interview someone and what to do before a new employee joins your team.
2b22ee8a-47ca-5bfd-9870-fd1bcca64d37.intro: Everyone who comes to work with us needs to have the right skills, knowledge and attitude. Our recruitment process is designed to help us consistently recruit the right people.
content: Before starting the recruitment process, think through what kind of contract is needed and what the job really involves, before getting agreement to recruit from your manager.

If you’re recruiting someone to work with children, young people or vulnerable adults, you’ll need to follow our minimum safer recruitment standards. This involves running DBS and other checks and paying extra attention to the CV and application form.

When you’ve got agreement to start looking for a new employee, you’ll need to speak to a Resourcing Consultant. They’ll get in touch with you to understand exactly who you’re looking for to join your team, and will talk you through our job advertising packages and assessment tools. They’ll help you decide on the right strategy to find the right person.

The way you write your advert could make a big difference to who applies for the job. It may be the first contact candidates have with us, so it’s vital that it gives the right first impression about working here. Focus on the specifics of the job, what knowledge and experience will allow someone to do it well and the benefits of working in your team.

Sometimes the easiest way to get someone quickly or with special skills is to use a recruitment agency. We use an agency called Pertemps for all our agency workers. You’ll need to fill in a vacancy approval form on SAP and carefully determine the person’s IR35 status

This is your opportunity to see who will perform well in the role. You’ll be able to assess the skills, knowledge and values of the candidates on your shortlist. And it’s a chance to get an idea of whether you’ll be able to work well together. Make sure that you plan interview dates from the start, so candidates can be told about them.

When you’ve made a decision about who you’d like to employ, you’re ready to offer them the job (you can ask your Resourcing Consultant to do it if you like). The Resourcing team will then send out the conditional offer email, and take up references and gather other information. They’ll also let the other candidates know they haven’t been successful. When your job offer has been accepted and the employment checks are done, it’s a good idea to call the successful candidate to make them feel welcome and start discussing their induction process.

When your candidate accepts our job offer, fill out a new starter form in our admin system, SAP. This means they’ll have access to the building and be issued with a laptop, and it will mean we can pay them.

faf2d81e-c32e-592a-9c42-a8e05c808176.title: If you have a problem at work
faf2d81e-c32e-592a-9c42-a8e05c808176.metaDescription: What to do if you have a problem with your work, working conditions or relationships with colleagues and how our grievance process works.
faf2d81e-c32e-592a-9c42-a8e05c808176.intro: If you have a problem with work, your working conditions or a colleague, it’s best to try and resolve it informally. However, you do have the right to raise a formal grievance.
content:
If you have a problem with something at work, you have the right to be heard. You won’t get into trouble by raising a problem and we’ll try and solve the issue as quickly as possible. 

However, you can’t use the grievance process as a way of attacking someone you don’t like if there’s no good reason. If you do so you could end up being disciplined. 
Before raising a grievance, it’s worth trying to sort things out simply by talking to whoever is involved if you can. 

This approach can be a quick way to clear up problems and improve your working relationship. There’s less room for misunderstandings when people talk face to face. 
If you can’t solve the issue face to face, you can raise an informal grievance by talking to your manager about it. If you have an issue with your manager, you can have a meeting with their manager. 

At the meeting you can explain the problems and your manager will explore the various ways that things could be resolved. 

These could include:

- Mediation – a process of open dialogue between you and the other person, facilitated by a neutral mediator, helping to find a constructive resolution.
- Practical solutions – where the problem is a practical issue such as your workstation, working hours etc.
- Counselling – advice, support and guidance, either for you or the person you have a problem with. 
- Training to modify behaviour – again, this could be for you or the other person.
If you’re not satisfied with the outcome of the informal grievance, you can raise or submit a formal grievance. You’ll need to submit your grievance in writing, and then a formal grievance meeting will be held. We might need to look into it further to establish the facts.

You’ll then be told what the decision is and whether your grievance has been upheld or not upheld, and you’ll have a chance to appeal. 
To find out more about grievances, look at our [Grievance Policy](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/2xojCENnFJBz3QnSYFFtf/3c18818f6c4734502f33b91e877f2c7e/BC_Grievance_Policy_v1.4_Mar_2020.doc "Grievance Policy")

1b06279f-e6c6-58e3-ba24-9633a33de0b7.title: Poor behaviour
1b06279f-e6c6-58e3-ba24-9633a33de0b7.metaDescription: How conduct issues are dealt with and our disciplinary process.
1b06279f-e6c6-58e3-ba24-9633a33de0b7.intro: Most conduct issues can be dealt with by an informal chat with your manager. But if that doesn't resolve things, or there’s a significant cause of concern, they may need to take things to a formal disciplinary process. In the most serious situations you could be asked to leave the council.
content:
Your manager will ask to meet you in a neutral place to talk. If your situation is connected to your line manager, then an independent manager will talk to you instead. You’ll get the chance to have a two-way open conversation and you’ll always be treated fairly.

Your manager will:

- Ask you to explain your behaviour
- Suggest how you can improve your behaviour
- Agree an action plan with you 
- Agree a review date to check how things are progressing

If your manager thinks the matter could be more serious, they may start a formal disciplinary procedure.
You may have to be suspended from work for a while so the situation can be investigated. 

You can still see your work colleagues socially, but you can’t discuss your situation. You should be contactable during work hours and, depending on how long the suspension goes on for, you’ll be paid as normal.

Your manager will review your suspension at least every month.

A suspension is not a punishment. It gives your manager and HR time to investigate your situation further.
Your manager will investigate your situation in more detail. They will tell you what they are looking into and why, unless this has something to do with children, young people or adults with care and support needs which is dealt with in a different way.

Your manager will meet with you in a preliminary investigation – a senior manager or director may decide if the investigation has to be formal. Your manager will then write to tell you the details of the investigation – for example, why you are being investigated and how long it will take. 

They will tell you:

- About the Investigating Officer who will look into your case and will always be impartial and independent from your situation
- About your rights
- If you are going to be suspended
- Other support available – for example, from your union

The investigating officer is there to establish the facts. They will find out what has happened and take a balanced view of all the information. 

They will:

- Talk to all the relevant people related to your case
- Read any statements and other information 
- Keep notes and records of everything that is said

You must cooperate with the investigation as much as you can. You can take a union representative or work colleague with you to any formal meetings.
After the investigation, a decision on next steps will be made. You may be asked to attend a disciplinary hearing.
You can choose to give evidence yourself or ask a representative to do this for you. The hearing will be chaired by the Hearing Officer. Someone from HR and a note taker will be there.

You will need to answer questions clearly and honestly. In some cases, it might be possible for your evidence to be recorded and shared in the hearing, or a presenting officer might present your evidence.

Once the hearing is over, your manager will make a decision, decide the penalty and let you know what’s decided. 

The penalty could include a written warning or being dismissed from the council.
You have the right to appeal against the outcome of your hearing. You must do this in writing within 5 working days of the appeal decision and give a written statement to your manager.

Your appeal will be reviewed and might lead to an appeal hearing. Depending on how serious the outcome is from your hearing, a different manager or senior manager will let you know what happens next. Once the appeal decision is made then this is final. Your manager will confirm the appeal decision in writing.

a3e7f56a-e94f-5781-be4b-e0443fbbe25b.title: Time off for parents
a3e7f56a-e94f-5781-be4b-e0443fbbe25b.metaDescription: This section explains the different kinds of leave available for parents, including maternity and paternity leave, adoption leave, shared parental leave and parental leave.
a3e7f56a-e94f-5781-be4b-e0443fbbe25b.intro:
Being a parent is challenging as well as rewarding, and we’ll do our best to help you through it. You can take paid time off when you have a new baby and when you’ve adopted, and unpaid parental leave as your children grow up. 

The amount of leave you can take will depend on your terms and conditions. The information on these pages is for staff employed on Buckinghamshire Council Terms and Conditions.

If you are on AVDC, BCC, C&SB, or WDC terms and conditions, your entitlement may be different. For more information click the links below:
content:
Having a baby is an exciting time, and you’ll probably have lots of questions around pay and maternity leave. You’ll be able to take up to 52 weeks’ time off, depending on how long you’ve worked here. 

The sooner you tell your manager the better, but you don’t need to tell them until 15 weeks before your due date (when you’re about 25 weeks pregnant) at the latest.
As the father of a new baby, or partner of a mother with a new baby, you can take two paid weeks off, as long as you’ve worked a certain amount of time with us.  

You can choose to split your maternity leave between you and the father (or your partner) during the first year after birth or adoption, as long as you’ve been working here long enough. 
You can get paid adoption leave if you’re newly matched with a child from an approved adoption agency. You’re entitled to this time off even if you recently started working here, although there will be differences in the amount of time off and pay. You need to start adoption leave at the time your child is placed with you or before. 
Parental leave is unpaid time off you can take if you have a child up to the age of 18. 

You can use this time to:

- Spend more time with your child or children
- Stay with your child in hospital
- Settle your child or children into new childcare arrangements

If you've worked for at least a year at the council, you can take up to four weeks’ parental leave a year, up to 18 weeks in total for each of your children.

da112398-bd93-58ee-bc3a-2ca5cf01e857.metaDescription: Details about paternity leave and how to apply for it.

You must take your paternity leave within 56 days of becoming the father or the other parent (either by birth or adoption). If your child is born early, then you can take paternity leave within the period from the actual date of birth up to 56 days after the expected week of childbirth. You’ll need to complete the [Paternity Leave Application Form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/7nmS7XbdT58jok3B7xAre5/b4eaa48a5ac10fe41dedaebfd66a495b/BC_paternity-leave-application-form-.doc "Paternity Leave Application Form") and send it to: HR Ops Team,

HP20 1UD Please also give a copy of the form to your line manager. You can take unpaid time off work to attend two antenatal appointments.

7dd0cb99-97ed-5091-9b50-85b2c5ddab36.title: Overtime
7dd0cb99-97ed-5091-9b50-85b2c5ddab36.metaDescription: Details of what happens when you work more than your normal hours, and whether you get paid overtime or given time off in lieu
7dd0cb99-97ed-5091-9b50-85b2c5ddab36.intro: There may be times when you’ll be asked to work more than your normal hours, but it should always be agreed in advance.
content: People on pay grade/range 5 or lower are paid for overtime. People in pay grade/ range 6 and above are given time off in lieu.
People who get paid for overtime receive time and a half for all hours worked (that’s 1.5 x your normal pay), except on Sundays, which will be at double time (2 x your normal pay).

- If you work less than half an hour a day extra, it won’t be counted as overtime.
- Overtime is calculated based on the number of complete half-hours.
- The half-hours are then added up over each calendar month and paid with your normal monthly salary.
- If you work part-time, any extra hours will be paid at the normal pay rate up to 37 hours per week. Any hours worked over your standard weekly hours will be paid at time and a half, or double time on Sundays.

If you have more than one part-time contract, overtime is calculated separately for each of the different contracts.

### Claiming online If you have access to SAP, use the online form to submit your overtime claim. You’ll get an automatic email once the claim has been approved. ### Using a paper form If you don't have access to SAP, then you’ll need to fill out a paper overtime claim form. Give it to your manager to authorise and then send it to: HR Operations,
8th Floor,
Walton Street Offices,
Walton Street,
Aylesbury
HP20 1AU. ### When you get paid Overtime claims approved online by the 12th of the month (or the previous working day if the 12th falls on a weekend or bank holiday) will be processed and paid in that month. Note that in December there’s an early payroll deadline, which usually falls around the 6th.

1da8d7d8-2e7f-5d4f-a958-36363a0df33d.title: How much you’re paid
1da8d7d8-2e7f-5d4f-a958-36363a0df33d.metaDescription: Find out how pay is determined, including details of pay ranges and contribution-based pay.
1da8d7d8-2e7f-5d4f-a958-36363a0df33d.intro: This information is for employees on Buckinghamshire County Council’s CBP Terms and Conditions.  Your pay depends on the pay range you’re in and the amount of contribution-based pay you receive. This is called Contribution Based Pay or CBP, and if you’re on CBP you’ll get a pay statement in July every year telling you how your performance relates to your salary

You will get a pay statement in July every year telling you how your performance relates to your salary. This will be recorded in your Delivering Successful Performance (DSP) record. 

Most people who do well in their jobs will be at the Competent point of pay, depending on their start date. But your salary can be decided anywhere between the Entry and Advanced point, and there is no single step move from Competent to Advanced. All pay progress depends on the CBP scheme. 

### No time-based increases
There are no time-based increases, so it doesn’t matter how long you’ve worked for us – your pay only goes up if you work well in your job. And your salary will never go down through the CBP scheme.

### No cost of living rises
Your salary also won’t change as the cost of living rises (or falls) – there are no inflation-based increases.

### Your CBP statement
You will receive a CBP statement in July which you can see online via SAP. The actual CBP pay review date is 1 July. Your performance rating applies to the pay range you were paid on 31 March, which is the end of the performance calculated year.

### How your pay is reviewed
If you want to understand how your pay is linked to your performance, you will need to know your:

- Delivering Successful Performance (DSP) rating
- Position in your pay range at 31 March.

Once you have this information you can work out how
your pay changes every July, using the [CBP Matrix.](https://intranet.buckscc.gov.uk/media/2174326/CBP-Matrix.docx "CBP Matrix")
If you’ve recently joined the council on CBP terms, you will usually be placed at the new starter level (entry point) on the pay range, unless there is a good reason to be placed above this.
If you get promoted, your pay rate will either be the entry point for your new pay range or 2.5% more than the pay you were getting – whichever is more.

Sometimes it's hard to fill certain posts, for example if they are very specific and need certain skills. We may need to offer more money to attract the right candidate. There will need to be a business case that sets this out as a need before we can go ahead and advertise the post.

If you’re working for us on a temporary contract from an agency, you may still be entitled to Contribution Based Pay. Your manager will set this up and review your work objectives with you so you can receive the appropriate hourly rate.

5d0ee4f5-0675-5a85-a8b5-d0203177ebd5.title: Carers' leave
5d0ee4f5-0675-5a85-a8b5-d0203177ebd5.metaDescription: Find out the arrangements for taking carers’ leave and how many days paid and unpaid leave you can take.
5d0ee4f5-0675-5a85-a8b5-d0203177ebd5.intro: If you’re a carer you can apply for paid time off if there’s an emergency affecting the person you look after, and unpaid time off in less urgent situations.
content:
The amount of leave you can take will depend on your terms and conditions. The information on below is for staff employed on Buckinghamshire Council Terms and Conditions.

If you are on AVDC, BCC, C&SB, or WDC terms and conditions, your entitlement may be different. For more information click the links below:

- [Aylesbury Vale District Council](https://avdc.app.box.com/folder/49049170045 "Aylesbury Vale District Council Information ")
- [Buckinghamshire County Council](https://intranet.buckscc.gov.uk/how-do-i/human-resources/what-you-can-expect-from-us/leave/carers-leave/ "Buckinghamshire County Council Information ")
- [Chiltern and South Bucks](https://crmstaff.chilternandsouthbucks.gov.uk/carers-leave "Chiltern and South Bucks Information ")

You can get paid carers’ leave if there’s a domestic emergency affecting your dependant and you absolutely need to be there. On each occasion there’s normally a maximum of two days’ paid leave, up to a total of five days over a year. The five days of paid carers' leave is taken from the same five day entitlement as paid compassionate leave.

You can also take unpaid leave if things are less serious, up to five days over a year. You can take up to 13 weeks’ unpaid leave while working at the council. 

If you work part time, you’re allowed a pro rata amount of carers’ leave.
You can ask for a temporary change in your working arrangements to make it easier to care for someone. This can be for up to four weeks and could include:

- Flexi-time
- Compressed hours
- Staggered hours
You’ll need to have worked for the council continuously for 26 weeks to apply for unpaid carers’ leave or to temporarily change your hours. Once you’ve made your request, your manager will either approve it or arrange a meeting to discuss it. 

Your manager’s decision will depend on the impact on the business, but if there’s no valid business reason to say no, your request should be approved.

bf1233ad-297e-5ca5-b714-035027b1b725.metaDescription: Details of how to apply for adoption leave, taking time off for adoption appointments care, Keeping in Touch days and what to do about coming back to work.

content:
You qualify for adoption leave however long (or short) you have worked for us. But you need to have worked for us for 26 weeks to be entitled to Statutory Adoption Pay.

Adoption leave can start up to 14 days before the date your new child is matched with you, but not after that date.
How much adoption leave you can take and the pay you get depends on how long you’ve worked here and your terms and conditions.
