- [Chiltern and South Bucks Information](https://crmstaff.chilternandsouthbucks.gov.uk/maternity-and-family-friendly "C&SB Information")
- [Wycombe District Council](https://wycopedia.wycombe.gov.uk/pages/Managers-toolkits/Managers-guidance/Maternity-paternity-and-adoption.aspx "WDC Information") 
Speak to your manager about your adoption plans as soon as possible. You can also talk to HR. 

You should tell your manager you want to take adoption leave within seven days of being told you’ve been matched with a child. You will also need to tell your manager:

- When the child is coming to live with you
- When you want your adoption leave to start – you can change this date with at least 28 days’ notice

You will also need to give them a Matching Certificate from the adoption agency which you can use to claim Statutory Adoption Leave and Pay.
Please fill out the [Maternity/Adoption Notification Form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/2E0nMGnULRmiU7lbYx2P2Y/49c9d94dba9a4394f7f18c711d952c2f/BC_maternity-adoption-notification-form.doc "Maternity/Adoption Notification Form") and give a copy to your manager and HR. You should do this as soon as you can.
If you’re the main adopting parent, you can take paid time off to go to up to five adoption appointments. The second adopting parent can take unpaid time off for up to two appointments. 
Keeping in touch (or KIT) days allow you to stay in touch with what’s happening at work while you’re on adoption leave.

You can get paid for up to 10 KIT days during your leave period without losing adoption leave or pay. 

Note that you can’t take KIT days in the first two weeks after the adoption of your child.

You don’t have to take KIT days unless you want to, and any work you do on these days has to be part of your normal employment contract. For example, you might want to use a KIT day to attend training.
You will need to fill out a [KIT days claim form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/5wxgM8xQFy8J2aw61X4Vi/746654d15d19459933d5183f2a60c501/KIT-days-claim-form.doc "KIT Days Claim Form") to be paid for the number of hours you attend work. This will be offset against any adoption pay for that week. 

The total amount you receive can’t be more than your normal full pay. Any payment for KIT days won’t affect your adoption pay or the length of adoption leave you want to take.

Whether you work one hour or a full day, this will count as one of your 10 KIT days.
It’s really helpful if you can keep your manager updated on your plans and when you want to come back to work. 

If you decide you want to return to work early, you must tell your manager in writing at least eight weeks before the you want to return to work. This will help them with any plans in place to cover your absence.

bac5dbcd-0842-5f23-8d44-31026bdde7b6.title: Shared parental leave
bac5dbcd-0842-5f23-8d44-31026bdde7b6.metaDescription: Details of how both parents or partners can share time off after having a child or adopting.
bac5dbcd-0842-5f23-8d44-31026bdde7b6.intro:
Shared parental leave gives you and your partner the chance to divide between you any remaining leave after the first two weeks after the birth or adoption. 

You need to have worked for a certain amount of time to qualify, but shared parental leave gives you and your partner more flexibility to care for and bond with your child.
content:
You need to take at least two weeks’ maternity leave after your child is born, or two weeks’ adoption leave, but after this you can share between you the up to 50 weeks’ leave remaining.

Shared parental leave has to be taken within the first year after the birth or placement of your child.
You must be the:

- Mother or adopting parent
- Birth father or spouse, civil partner or partner of the child’s mother / adopting parent

You must have worked for the council for 26 weeks by the end of the 15th week before your baby is due or the expected date you’ll be matched with a child for adoption.
Your partner must have been employed for 26 weeks out of the 66 weeks (not necessarily continuously) before the week your baby is due to be born, or the week you’re told that you’ve been matched with a child for adoption.

They must have earned at least £30 a week on average during any 13 of those weeks, but again not necessarily continuously.

If your partner hasn’t been working or is self-employed, they won’t be entitled to take shared parental leave.
If both parents want to take shared parental leave, then you can take your leave at the same time or at different times.

Shared parental leave must be:

- For at least one week
- Taken in multiples of whole weeks
- Taken as one period or up to three separate periods of time

This means you or your partner can go back to work after maternity / adoption leave is over but still take shared parental leave at a later date.

The father or partner can take shared parental leave at any time. You can also take it when the other partner is on paternity leave or unpaid parental leave.
If you want to end maternity / adoption leave early so you can take advantage of shared parental leave, you need to tell your manager at least eight weeks earlier. 
 
You can give notice to end maternity / adoption leave before or after the birth or matching date, but if it’s after then it is binding and you won’t be able to restart your maternity leave and pay. If you give notice before the birth or matching date, you can always change back up to six weeks after the birth / matching date.
 
Please fill out the [Maternity / Adoption Leave Curtailment Notice](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/5GfqYM2YwJ27O6uTbbv5pO/75fee68a07442ac55b89e89a6a1e52d5/spl-maternity-adoption-leave-curtailment-notice.docx "Maternity/Adoption Leave Curtailment Notice") and give it to your manager and HR.
You must fill out the [Notice of Entitlement and Intention form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/4OGbom58FIlODul3eZjCui/f78b716b27173b2a9770e5f35a10b52b/spl-notice-of-entitlement-and-intention-mother-adopter.docx "Notice of Entitlement and Intention form") and give this to your manager eight weeks before you want shared parental leave to start.
 
You can vary the amount of shared parental leave you want to take by writing to your manager. Please use the [Variation of Notice of Entitlement and Intention form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/VdUwr5pGEEVH7ZlhGiZFw/40d6af362e5dc194a9891d80b72f09fb/spl-variation-of-notice-of-entitlement-and-intention.docx "Variation of Notice of Entitlement and Intention form")
 
There is no limit on the number of times you can make changes to shared parental leave, so long as this is done before the formal [Period of Leave Notice](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/2Jsks4pC5y50RRHd12Y0in/a51ffd31539894d6b7c07291d1bf5bbf/spl-period-of-leave-notice.docx "Period of Leave Notice") has been given.
 
Only three Period of Leave notices can be given by each parent. This includes requests to vary a period of leave that has already been arranged.
 
If you ask for one continuous period of leave, then you'll be able to take this, but your manager can say no to requests for periods of discontinuous leave.
 
Once they have agreed the times with you, they will sign any forms and send them to HR. You should get a letter back confirming everything in writing.
You can take 20 paid days’ work during your leave period without losing your entitlement to Shared Parental Leave or pay. These are called Shared Parental Leave in Touch or SPLIT days. 

SPLIT days help you to keep in touch with any developments at work. You don’t have to work SPLIT days and your manager can’t make you work these days.

You can claim for SPLIT days by completing a [SPLIT days claim form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/nE4wDUhAGWq0zAob8wpCV/0bc01c56eeb48987bbf3f6b989c834a0/SPLIT-days-claim-form.doc "SPLIT Days Claim Form"). You’ll be paid for the number of hours you work, but the total amount you receive can’t be more than your normal full pay.  

Whether you work one hour or a full day, this will count as one of your 20 SPLIT days. If your manager agrees, you could use SPLIT days to work part of a week during your shared parental leave.

aede058d-d026-5ea3-b8cf-a5eeb99267a8.title: Priority for new roles
aede058d-d026-5ea3-b8cf-a5eeb99267a8.metaDescription: Find out who is considered first for an available role out of people on the Employee Transfer Register
aede058d-d026-5ea3-b8cf-a5eeb99267a8.intro: When several people on the Employee Transfer Register all meet the essential criteria for a role, anyone facing redundancy takes priority, and anyone facing redundancy and on maternity, adoption, or shared parental leave has top priority.

004d5acc-7653-5814-b746-b39d719f5b2a.title: Joining the register
004d5acc-7653-5814-b746-b39d719f5b2a.metaDescription: Find out who can join the Employee Transfer Register and how to join it
004d5acc-7653-5814-b746-b39d719f5b2a.intro: If you’re eligible to join the Employee Transfer Register then you simply need to fill in a form and send it to HR. Depending on your circumstances you may be entitled to the same pay as before, even in a lower paid role.
content:
You can join the register if you’ve been given notice of redundancy. 

If you find a new position which pays less than your old one, you may be entitled to pay protection.  The amount of pay protection you may get will depend on your terms and conditions, but during this time you’ll be given priority for any new roles that pay your original salary level. 


Once you’ve been given notice towards the end of your fixed term contract you can join the register. 

If your contract ends earlier than originally agreed as part of a restructure you’ll be entitled to pay protection. This means that if you find a new job which pays less than your old one, you’ll be paid at your previous level.
If you have a disability which means you can’t continue in your current role, you can join the register to help you find a new position. 

This will only happen after reasonable adjustments to your role have been explored.
If you are unable to work because of illness, even after a plan has been put in place, and have had a formal meeting to decide what happens next, you can join the register. 
Download and fill in the [Employee Transfer Register referral form (Word doc, 30k)](https://intranet.buckscc.gov.uk/media/3287486/Employee-Transfer-Register-Referral-Form-August-2019.docx), and send it through to the HR at [hrservicedesk@buckscc.gov.uk](mailto:hrservicedesk@buckscc.gov.uk "hrservicedesk@buckscc.gov.uk").

e4c5a43d-fcad-5d71-9189-846066f7883c.title: Sick pay scheme
e4c5a43d-fcad-5d71-9189-846066f7883c.metaDescription: Find out what happens to your pay when you take time off sick, and how long full pay lasts depending on how long you’ve worked at the council.
e4c5a43d-fcad-5d71-9189-846066f7883c.intro: If you’re off sick you will still get paid for a period. You’ll be on full pay at first, but after a time this will change to half pay. How long this lasts depends on how long you’ve worked for us.
content:
Full payHalf pay
During 1st year of service 1 month + 2 months (after completing 4 months' service)
During 2nd year of service 2 months + 2 months
During 3rd year of service 4 months + 4 months
During 4th and 5th years of service 5 months + 5 months
After 5 years of service 6 months + 6 months
Sick pay is calculated on a 12 month basis, so any time off ill in the past 12 months reduces your allowance available now. Sometimes, very rarely, sick pay can carry on for longer. Your manager will need to speak to HR and also get the agreement of the director for your area before this can happen.

3286bd0a-7e55-5ae2-aa5e-01bd36ca4460.title: Sabbaticals
3286bd0a-7e55-5ae2-aa5e-01bd36ca4460.metaDescription: How to take unpaid time off from work for top pursue your own interests without having to resign from your position at the council.
3286bd0a-7e55-5ae2-aa5e-01bd36ca4460.intro:
A sabbatical is a chance to take up to a year off without having to permanently stop working at the council.

A sabbatical is an unpaid period of time away from work. It’s a way of doing something you would otherwise not have time to do, and the benefits could enhance your career or your skills or just give you new experiences.
content:
The information on this page is for staff employed on Buckinghamshire Council Terms and Conditions, but also applies to staff employed on Buckinghamshire County Council terms. If you work for the council on any other terms and conditions and need information regarding sabbaticals, please speak with your manager or contact the HR team through the [Service Desk Portal](https://buckscprod.service-now.com/sp "Service Desk Portal"), email us at [hrservicedesk@buckinghamshire.gov.uk](mailto:hrservicedesk@buckinghamshire.gov.uk), or call us on [01296 382233](tel:01296382233 "Telephone us")

- You need to have been employed continuously for two years at the council or elsewhere in local government.
- You can’t be on a Performance Improvement Plan (PIP) for capability or performance issues.
- You can’t have a ‘live’ discipline warning or currently be managed through issues relating to conduct and discipline.

You need to apply in writing to your manager and then have a meeting with them.
You won’t automatically be given a sabbatical. It depends on the impact on the
business and how easily your role can be covered, as well as the benefits to you of the time off.

375d0076-1e17-57d4-8fa6-23ed59e0e0bc.title: Pay and money
375d0076-1e17-57d4-8fa6-23ed59e0e0bc.metaDescription: This section covers how pay works, including payslips, changing your bank details, your P60 and P45, overtime and how contribution based pay works.
375d0076-1e17-57d4-8fa6-23ed59e0e0bc.intro: This section gives quick answers about your pay, payslips, overtime and more.
content: Most employees get paid on the last working day of the month.

You get a new payslip each month, showing how much you’re paid that month, any deductions (like tax) and some other details. You can see all your payslips right back to when you started working here on the SAP Launchpad via ESS portal. 

You can also view your payslips on [Epay](https://epay.myaceni.co.uk/buckspay/login.html "Link to Epay")

Instructions of how to access your Epay account will be emailed to you when your first Epay payslip is available to view. 

Your User Name will be your National Insurance number with no spaces and all in capital letters.

If you are logging in for the first time, the password is within the welcome email which would have been sent to you.

If re-setting your password, it needs to include 1 capital letter and 1 number and needs to be at least 8 characters long.

You will need to set 3 security questions of your choice.

The answers to the security questions which you set need to be at least 6 characters long.

If you forget your password or security questions please click on the links available to reset these. 

If you still require assistance or haven't received your log in instructions by your first pay day please contact the HR team through the [Service Desk Portal](https://buckscprod.service-now.com/sp "Service Desk Portal"), email us at [hrservicedesk@buckinghamshire.gov.uk](mailto:hrservicedesk@buckinghamshire.gov.uk), or call us on [01296 382233](tel:01296382233 "Telephone us")

You can change your bank details by logging into the SAP Employee Self Service Portal. You’ll need to change your bank details by the 12th of the month to be paid into that account at the end of the month.

You can view your P60 on the Epay site, depending on when you started working here. Your P60 is a summary of your total pay and tax each full financial year (which runs from 6 April to 5 April). 

You should receive your P60 every year by 31 May.

> A P60 is proof of your income so it can be an important document if you’re applying for a loan or mortgage. Your P60 can't be used to update your tax code.

When you start working with us we’ll need your P45 so we can put you on the right tax code and pay you the right amount. Your P45 is a record of all your pay and
tax taken so far in the current tax year. 

If you don’t have a P45 (for example if you haven’t been employed before), you’ll need to fill out an [HMRC starter checklist](https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/paye-starter-checklist "Link to PAYE starter checklist").

Without a P45 or starter checklist you may be put on a Zero T or 0T tax code, which could mean you’re taxed more than you should be. You may be entitled to get your money back, but it may take some time, and you might need to [contact HMRC directly.](https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/hm-revenue-customs/contact/income-tax-enquiries-for-individuals-pensioners-and-employees "Contact HMRC")
If you haven’t been paid the right amount, either too little or too much, it needs to be sorted out as soon as possible.

If you work overtime you will either get paid extra or, for those at grade/range 6 and above, get time off in lieu.

Overtime is usually paid at a rate of a time and a half for people working over 37 hours a week, and double time on Sunday. The extra pay is paid monthly with your normal salary.

How much you’re paid depends on your terms and conditions. Use the links below to find out more information:

- [Aylesbury Vale District Council Pay Information](https://avdc.app.box.com/folder/49049170045 "Aylesbury Vale District Council Pay Information")
- [Buckinghamshire Council Pay Information](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/2OqkT1O9X9GwviR9ndkAZN/61dab66acf5366afe88ed7d4228f5471/Buckinghamshire_Council_Pay_Information.rtf)
- [Buckinghamshire County Council Contribution Based Pay Information](https://youandwork.buckscc.gov.uk/pay-money/how-much-youre-paid "Buckinghamshire County Council CBP Information")
- [Chiltern and South Bucks Pay Information ](https://crmstaff.chilternandsouthbucks.gov.uk/pay "Chiltern and South Bucks Pay Information")
- [Wycombe District Council Pay Information ](https://wycopedia.wycombe.gov.uk/pages/My-employment/Employment-policies/Pay-policy.aspx "Wycombe District Council Pay Information")

2acc0c90-b209-52a6-9730-136fc6920a32.title: Your trial period
2acc0c90-b209-52a6-9730-136fc6920a32.metaDescription: What happens during the four week trial period at the start of a new role that’s significantly different from your previous one
2acc0c90-b209-52a6-9730-136fc6920a32.intro: When you start a role that’s significantly different from your previous one, your first four weeks are a trial period for you and your manager to see if the role suits you.
content:
You have up to four weeks to decide if the new role is suitable for you, but the sooner you can decide the better. The period can be extended if there’s a good reason to do so, for example if you need training before you can start the role properly. 

- If you decide the role isn’t suitable for you, arrange a meeting with your manager as soon as possible. 
- If your manager decides it’s not suitable for you, they will arrange a meeting with you within the four week trial period.  
- If you both agree that the role isn’t suitable, you’ll be able to take your original redundancy payment. 
- If your manager thinks the role is suitable but you don’t want to accept it, you may not get your original redundancy payment.  
- If you keep working beyond the end of the trial period without discussing the role’s suitability, we’ll assume that you’ve accepted the role. 

If your manager decides the role isn’t suitable for you, you’ll still get your original redundancy payment. 

- If your original notice period hasn’t yet finished, you’ll return to your original role or else go on ‘management leave’. Until the notice period ends you’ll stay on the Employee Transfer Register, and if no alternative role comes up you’ll then stop working.  
- If your notice period has ended you’ll immediately stop work.

9e94d6f2-39a1-5bb7-b5d8-2fbff9dfbd1c.title: What suitable alternative employment means
9e94d6f2-39a1-5bb7-b5d8-2fbff9dfbd1c.metaDescription: Find out what is considered suitable alternative employment and when you might be offered it.
9e94d6f2-39a1-5bb7-b5d8-2fbff9dfbd1c.intro: If your current role is being made redundant, you may be offered another role that is similar enough to be considered suitable alternative employment. If you don’t want to accept this you won’t be entitled to a redundancy payment.
content:
Suitable alternative employment has to be broadly similar to your previous role in terms of duties and responsibilities, how much you’re paid and where you’ll work. The terms and conditions can’t be substantially worse for you than your current ones. 

All these points are considered:

- Salary
- Conditions of employment
- Duties and responsibilities
- Location
- Skills, knowledge and experience
- Aptitude and potential
- Training and re-training opportunities
- Special individual circumstances

If you want to apply for jobs at a higher level, you’ll go through the normal recruitment process rather than automatically getting an interview if you meet the essential criteria.
If you’ve been on a permanent contract, you may be offered a fixed term contract, and this will be considered a suitable alternative employment. We would typically use a fixed term contract to keep you working here while we try to find another permanent role. 

After taking a fixed term contract, you can rejoin the register once you’ve been served notice. If you can’t find another role at that point you’ll receive your redundancy pay.
If you don’t want to take the suitable alternative employment you’re offered, refuse an interview for a role, or resign without good reason during a trial period, you may lose any redundancy pay you would have been owed. 

Your manager will meet with you to find out your reasons (you can be accompanied by a trade union representative or a colleague). If they conclude that you’ve unreasonably refused the role, you’ll lose your redundancy entitlement.

cea81086-5dff-5afd-84a0-24697fae4cc4.title: Maternity leave
cea81086-5dff-5afd-84a0-24697fae4cc4.metaDescription: Find out how to apply for maternity leave, time off for antenatal care, Keeping in Touch days and what to do about coming back to work.
cea81086-5dff-5afd-84a0-24697fae4cc4.intro: Having a baby is a life-changing experience and you’ll be able to take plenty of time off work to deal with it. You’ll need to fill in a form to apply for maternity leave.
content:
Everyone must take at least two weeks’ maternity leave, but how much additional time off you can take and the pay you get will depend on how long you’ve worked for us and how much you get paid. Typically you’ll have some time at 90% of full pay, followed by a period on a lower rate. 

You’ll find full details in our [Family Friendly Guidance](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/3KS9J2G1w1r2Hn7nxbph70/ee7e776e5babc300c36feccf5cdf530b/BC_Family_Friendly_Guidance_Mar_2020.doc "Family Friendly Guidance"), attached below.

How much time you can take off and the pay you get will depend on your terms and conditions. The information on this page, and in our Family Friendly Leave Guidance,  is for staff employed on Buckinghamshire Council Terms and Conditions.

If you are on AVDC, BCC, C&SB, or WDC terms and conditions, your entitlement may be different. For more information and to find any forms you may need please use the links below:

- [Aylesbury Vale District Council](https://avdc.app.box.com/folder/49049170045 "Aylesbury Vale District Council Information ")
- [Buckinghamshire County Council](https://intranet.buckscc.gov.uk/how-do-i/human-resources/what-you-can-expect-from-us/leave/maternity-leave/ "BCC Information ")
- [Chiltern and South Bucks](https://crmstaff.chilternandsouthbucks.gov.uk/maternity-and-family-friendly "Chiltern and South Bucks Information") 
- [Wycombe District Council](https://wycopedia.wycombe.gov.uk/pages/Managers-toolkits/Managers-guidance/Maternity-paternity-and-adoption.aspx "Wycombe District Council Information ") 
Tell your manager your pregnancy due date when you feel comfortable doing so. But remember that the sooner you do the easier it will be for your manager to plan for your absence. 

> You must tell your manager you’re pregnant by the end of the 15th week before the week you’re expected to give birth.

You should also let them know the date you want your maternity leave to start. You can always change this date with at least 28 days’ notice.

Please fill out the [Maternity/Adoption Notification form ](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/9Lbl4tfCj6VlLCcfFozDJ/e04cda94cc4a5b79f381122dd716a4f5/BC_maternity-adoption-notification-form.doc "Maternity/Adoption Notification Form") and give a copy to your manager and HR. You should do this as soon as you can.

You should also get a MATB1 form from your doctor or a registered midwife and hand it in with the notification form.

We will write to you within 28 days to confirm your expected due date and the date you are expected back at work.
Your manager will: 

- Assess any risks for you at work when you are pregnant – you can read more in the [Expectant Mother's Risk Assessment](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/1F1yKEKRwIoRiACBrPic6g/91671e772c7b0f8a04168c9aea3f79b4/H_S_Maternity.doc "Expectant Mother's Risk Assessment").

- Talk to you about your work progress and update this in your record 

- Meet with you to review your work achievements before you start your maternity leave
You should get paid time off for all your antenatal appointments. This includes antenatal care for relaxation and parenting classes as well as medical appointments.

### What your manager needs to see
Aside from your first appointment, your manager will ask to see evidence of appointments with medical practitioners including midwives and health visitors.

The father or partner can get unpaid time off work to attend two antenatal appointments.
Keeping in touch (or KIT) days allow you to stay in touch with what’s happening at work while you’re on maternity leave. For example, you might want to use a KIT day to attend training.

You can get paid for up to up to 10 KIT days during your maternity leave. 

You don’t have to take KIT days unless you want to and any work you do on these days has to be part of your normal employment contract. 
Fill out a [KIT days claim form](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/4oh4rK2vMqzLo5O5lds0Si/1cb38911b13ccb1e314459bcc102a3b1/KIT-days-claim-form.doc "KIT days claim form") and you’ll be paid for the number of hours you’re at work. This will be offset against any maternity pay for that week. 

The total amount you receive can’t be more than your normal full pay. Any payment for KIT days won’t affect your maternity allowance / maternity pay or the length of maternity leave you want to take.

Whether you work one hour or a full day, this will count as one of your 10 KIT days.
It’s really helpful if you can keep your manager updated on your plans and when you want to come back to work. 

If you decide you want to return to work early, you must tell your manager in writing at least eight weeks before you want to return to work. This will help them with any plans in place to cover your absence.

e1a28cf2-a946-5e2c-85ef-03f36ca75650.title: Behaviour at work
e1a28cf2-a946-5e2c-85ef-03f36ca75650.metaDescription: This section covers how you’re expected to behave at work, how we tackle problems with your conduct, grievance and whistleblowing.
e1a28cf2-a946-5e2c-85ef-03f36ca75650.intro: We all have a responsibility to behave well at work. This section explains the standards of conduct we’re expected to meet, our disciplinary process, what to do if you have a problem at work, and how to complain if you’re concerned about someone else’s behaviour.
content: When we’re working at the council we should conduct ourselves to high standards. This includes being respectful to the people we work with as well as behaving ethically. Ultimately we’re guided by our Code of Conduct.

If your conduct falls below our standards then it needs to be tackled. Most of the time it can be dealt with through an informal chat with your manager, but if it’s more serious then you may have to go to a disciplinary meeting.

We want you to be happy at work. But if something isn’t right or you’re not being treated well then you can do something about it. For example, if you feel you’ve been harassed or bullied then you must tell your manager as soon as possible.

Whistleblowing is when you report someone else for doing something that you think is dangerous, illegal or unethical. Don’t try to deal with this kind of situation yourself – always report it as soon as you can.

aacf6b73-c564-5892-ab86-6407315ca602.title: Whistleblowing
aacf6b73-c564-5892-ab86-6407315ca602.metaDescription: What to do if you’re concerned that a colleague is doing something dangerous or illegal.
aacf6b73-c564-5892-ab86-6407315ca602.intro: If you think someone else at the council is doing something dangerous, illegal or unethical, then you should report it. You’re legally protected from being treated badly because of reporting something.
content:
Whistleblowing is when someone believes that someone else at work is doing something dangerous to others, breaking the law or acting unethically, and reports them for it. 

Here are some of the reasons you might raise concerns:

- Damage to the environment
- Abuse of clients
- Safeguarding concerns relating to children, young people or adults with care and support needs.
- Health and Safety risks
- Fraud or corruption 
- Unauthorised use of council funds 
- Unfair pressures on staff

You don’t need to have proof, you just need to have reasonable concerns (but you can’t just be complaining about a colleague you don’t like).

As a council, we want our people to work to high standards, and we want to hear about it if anyone is abusing their position here.
If you raise a concern you think is in the public interest, you’re legally protected by the Public Interest Disclosure Act 1998. You can’t be treated badly at work because of it. 

Equally, if you think someone has blown the whistle on someone else, you shouldn’t treat them badly for it. You could be disciplined if you do. 
First of all you should tell your manager about your concerns. If you’re concerned about your manager then tell their manager. 

If you’re worried about telling your manager or their manager, you can use our Whistleblowing Hotline on [01296 382237](tel:01296382237 "Whistleblowing hotline") (accessible 24 hours a day) or email [audit@buckinghamshire.gov.uk](mailto:audit@buckinghamshire.gov.uk "Email whistleblowing audit"). 

And if you’re worried about someone who works with children, young people or vulnerable adults, you can tell a Local Authority Designated Officer (LADO) on [01296 382070](tel:01296382070 "Local Authority Designated Officer").
You can raise a concern and ask for it to be kept confidential. If so we won’t let anyone know about your involvement. 

You can also raise an issue anonymously through the Whistleblowing Hotline, but it could make it harder for us to investigate things. 
After having a meeting with you to find out more, your manager can then take action or launch an investigation. This could end up leading to a full internal investigation or even, in serious cases, getting the police involved. The council will let you know what action is being taken and the outcome. In more serious cases, the council might not be able to let you know the full details.

At the end of the process, if you’re not satisfied with what the council has done you can raise your concern with someone outside the council. You can talk to:

- A county councillor or MP
- The District Auditor
- The police
- Public Concern at Work (www.pcaw.co.uk or 020 7404 6609)
- A relevant professional body or inspectorate (e.g. Ofsted)
- A trade union or professional association
- The Local Government Ombudsman
To find out more details about whistleblowing, look at our [Whistleblowing Policy](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/3Did75SDR3zk2nUID6FzIj/681ca3f7af7f7fb4b1c97da6aed11a98/Whistleblowing_Policy.rtf).

fca748c6-63b8-53ec-bd99-05982b0d7762.title: Frequent illness
fca748c6-63b8-53ec-bd99-05982b0d7762.metaDescription: Details of what happens if you’re sick frequently or regularly – your manager will need to talk to you about it.
fca748c6-63b8-53ec-bd99-05982b0d7762.intro: If you’re often ill or off work, we will need to find out more about why this is happening, and then do what we can to help find a solution.
content:
- You’re away from work for more than 3 days in any 6-month period 
- There’s a pattern of being away on the same day or days in a week, or around special occasions 

If either of these apply, your manager will need to find out more. We understand that everyone goes through periods of short-term illness, but we need you to be clear and honest with us. It might be that your absence isn’t because you’re ill, but we still need to find out what’s going on. 

We have a standard process for dealing with people who are ill or off work regularly. Following this helps us to do all we can to improve your attendance in the future.

### Stage 1 – informal meeting
Your manager will set up a meeting to find out more about your situation. It’s important you attend meetings that your manager arranges.

Your manager will need to find out more about your reasons for being off work. They might ask you to see an occupational health adviser who specialises in the well-being of people at work. The health adviser will talk to you about any problems you’re facing and the reasons why you’re off work ill regularly. They may ask to see a medical report from your GP before writing up their report on your situation.

Your manager will talk through the health adviser’s report with you and agree a plan to review your situation regularly. If you need support at work because of health issues, your manager will do what they can to help you. For example, they might change your working pattern for a limited time or your role at work so your attendance can improve.

Your manager will arrange a follow up meeting to see whether you are back on track.

### Stage 2 – formal meeting
If your absence hasn’t improved after the plan has been put into action, you’ll need to attend a formal meeting. You can take a work colleague with you or someone from your Union if you want to. If you haven't already spoken with occupational health, your manager might ask you to talk to a health adviser. Your manager will look at all the information and decide what to do next.

This could include reducing your work hours or bringing in special equipment to help you at work. We’ll follow our Health and Attendance policy and the Equality Act 2010 at every stage.

[Health and Attendance Policy](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/6Ramm6Mt2ISpE8pahajgAB/ff98bf0eaecbef2895de7941a92e54ac/BC_Health_and_Attendance_Policy_v1.4_Mar_2020.doc)

Your manager will arrange another follow up meeting to see if you're improving and decide what to do next.


### Stage 3 – final options
If there is not enough improvement in your attendance, then your manager will either suggest changes to the arrangements brought in at Stage 2 or consider whether you need to stop working at the council. If we find out you’ve not been ill but still not been at work, then we will also need to follow our [Conduct and Discipline Policy](//assets.ctfassets.net/fxzi1pcakms5/6J1DsxT4xfLPiITWe0dIA5/42b546ff2cbde0eb4cdbe9255fd69f96/BC_Conduct_and_Discipline_Policy_v1.4_Mar_2020.doc) and you could receive a formal warning.

fe3f9ede-3813-5f6c-9e83-a0f8e3623ce1.title: Parental leave
fe3f9ede-3813-5f6c-9e83-a0f8e3623ce1.metaDescription: Find out how you can take unpaid time off to spend with your child up to the age of 18, taking up to four weeks a year.
fe3f9ede-3813-5f6c-9e83-a0f8e3623ce1.intro: You can take up to 4 weeks’ unpaid parental leave a year to spend time with your child up to the age of 18, as long as you’ve worked at the council for at least a year.
content:
You can take up to 18 weeks’ unpaid parental leave for each of your children. This total includes any parental leave you were given by a previous employer. 

You can take parental leave in week-long blocks, up to a maximum of four weeks’ parental leave a year. If your child is disabled, you can take the leave one day at a time or more. 
You can request parental leave using the SAP Portal.

Your manager will have to approve any leave requests.

1b901a42-c3f2-52c5-b1fe-035e048084f7.title: Compassionate leave
1b901a42-c3f2-52c5-b1fe-035e048084f7.metaDescription: Find out how to take time off if you have serious personal problems to deal with.
1b901a42-c3f2-52c5-b1fe-035e048084f7.intro: If you need to be away from work to deal with serious personal problems at home, you can apply for compassionate leave.
content:
Each request for compassionate leave will be judged individually, but you can use the following as guidelines:

- Death or serious illness of a close relative (spouse, partner, child, parent, brother, sister or grandparent).
- A domestic emergency which affects a dependent, i.e. a spouse, partner, child, parent, someone living in the same house as you (except lodgers, etc) or someone dependent on you for assistance. 

Essentially, if there are unforeseen problems and your presence is critical, you’re likely to qualify for compassionate leave.
To apply for compassionate leave, speak to your manager and explain the situation. 
Then go to the SAP Portal Employee Self Service (ESS) choose ‘Leave Request’ ‘comp’nate leave (paid)’ or ‘comp’nate leave (unpaid)’.
The Service Director will decide if you get paid time off, depending on your circumstances.
There’s normally a limit of five days’ paid compassionate leave per year, but you may be able to take more unpaid time off. In exceptional circumstances more paid time off will be given.

The information above is for staff employed on Buckinghamshire Council Terms and Conditions.

If you are on AVDC, BCC, C&SB, or WDC terms and conditions, how much paid time off you can have may be different. For more information click the links below:

- [Aylesbury Vale District Council](https://avdc.app.box.com/folder/49049170045 "Aylesbury Vale District Council Information ")
- [Buckinghamshire County Council](https://intranet.buckscc.gov.uk/how-do-i/human-resources/what-you-can-expect-from-us/leave/compassionate-leave/ "Buckinghamshire County Council Information ")
- [Chiltern and South Bucks](https://crmstaff.chilternandsouthbucks.gov.uk/compassionate-leave "Chiltern and South Bucks Information ")
- [Wycombe District Council](https://wycopedia.wycombe.gov.uk/pages/My-employment/Employment-policies/Local-terms-and-conditions-of-employment.aspx "Wycombe District Council Information ")

73501314-3e44-58d8-9c6b-07d2849f7e52.title: Problems with pay
73501314-3e44-58d8-9c6b-07d2849f7e52.metaDescription: Find out what to do if you’ve been paid too much or too little, or not been paid at all
73501314-3e44-58d8-9c6b-07d2849f7e52.intro: If you haven’t been paid the right amount, it’s important we know quickly so we can do something about it.
content:
You may think you’ve been paid too little. There are a number of reasons why this
might happen.

### Not paid for overtime
If you haven’t been paid overtime, it could be that it wasn’t approved in time. If so, it will be in your next payslips.

### Paid too much tax
If you think you’ve paid too much tax, it might be because you recently started working here and haven’t given us a P45 form or filled in a new starter form. See the [New starters and P45 page to find out more](https://youandwork.buckscc.gov.uk/pay-money/new-starters-and-p45).

If there’s any other problem with your tax, you’ll need to [contact HM Revenue and
Customs (HMRC) directly](https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/hm-revenue-customs/contact/income-tax-enquiries-for-individuals-pensioners-and-employees "External link to the HMRC website").

If you haven’t been paid at all, contact the HR team through the [Service Desk Portal](https://buckscprod.service-now.com/sp "Service Desk Portal"), email at [hrservicedesk@buckinghamshire.gov.uk](mailto:hrservicedesk@buckinghamshire.gov.uk), or call on [01296 382233](tel:01296382233 "Telephone us") and they'll do their best to sort it out as soon as possible.

If you’re paid more than you should be, you will need to pay it back.

### Tell your manager
As soon as you realise you’ve been overpaid, tell your manager about it. They will find out how you can pay back the extra amount you’ve been paid. If you don’t mention it you may have to go through a disciplinary procedure and could end up losing your job.

### Getting the money back
The council has the right to take the extra money back, and in the end we will do all we can to get it (after all, the money the council has comes from people’s taxes). 

For example, the amount in your next pay packet might be reduced. But however it happens, you’ll be told about it before anything is done.

If you were paid too much over a long period, you won’t have to pay it back all at once but the aim will be to recover the money within a year.

If you leave the council before paying the money back, we’ll still work to get it back, if necessary through our Legal Recovery Service.

dde2cdb1-f97b-58ab-9190-088f16768ccc.title: Accessibility statement for Buckinghamshire County Council
dde2cdb1-f97b-58ab-9190-088f16768ccc.metaDescription: Accessibility statement for Buckinghamshire County Council
dde2cdb1-f97b-58ab-9190-088f16768ccc.intro:
This website is run by Buckinghamshire County Council. We want as many people as possible to be able to use this website. For example, that means you should be able to:

- change colours, contrast levels and fonts
- zoom in up to 300% without the text spilling off the screen
- navigate most of the website using just a keyboard
- navigate most of the website using speech recognition software
- listen to most of the website using a screen reader (including the most recent versions of JAWS, NVDA and VoiceOver)
- We’ve also made the website text as simple as possible to understand.

AbilityNet has advice on making your device easier to use if you have a disability.
